description:
Graphic artist and Civil War aficionado C. M. Butzer deftly uses a detailed, comic-book style to depict the Battle of Gettysburg; the national movement to create a memorial there; and the quiet day in 1863 when Lincoln delivered his galvanizing speech. Butzer uses only primary sources for the text, drawing from first-person letters and diaries, speeches, and Lincoln's own writing to unpack this series of historical events. The address itself is played out over eighteen pages, with every phrase given a visual interpretation  .
 
Aimed at 9 -14 year olds, this Graphic Novel is 80 pages long and printed using black, white, gray & blue as the only colors
name: Gettysburg: The Graphic Novel

description:
Official Volume Solicitation  

How far would you go to meet your favorite boy band? Kum-Ji was little late getting under the spell of the chart topping boy band DDL. Unable to join the DDL fan club, she almost gives up meeting her idols until she develops a cunning plan, becoming a top member of their rival fan club for a brand-new boy group, Yo-I (Chocolat). This way she can always be near Yo-I at all their concerts. Funnily enough Yo-I always seem to play the same shows with DDL. It’s almost the perfect plan except it’s really complicated being a super fan for one band when your heart lies with another. Follow the adventures of Kum-Ji in this full-blown romantic comedy as she tries to keep her scheme together. 

Publishing History

The series was originally distributed in the US & other English speaking countries through Ice Kunion , who specialised in manhwa from South Korea.  However, Ice Kunion suffered financial difficulties and was ultimately absorbed by Yen Press .  The graphic novel & manga imprint of the Hachette Book Group took over the distribution of all Ice Kunion's previous titles from the next numbered volume and retained the presentational format of the books to please readers.   
 
Therefore, volumes 1 to 3 were published by Ice Kunion, while volumes 4 onwards were published by Yen Press. 
 
Chocolat is the fourth collaborative series from Shin JiSang & Geo.  Although the seventh volume ended with a cliff-hanger with no sign of an eighth ready for publication, the official Chocolat page on Yen Press' website made an announcement that the boys of Yo-I hadn't split up and would be back soon.
name: Chocolat

description:
Solicitation

Orange has become so nihilistic about her life - callous parents, shallow friends, meaningless relationships - that she decides the only way out is to kill herself. But as she is about to jump, a mysterious man stops her, convincing her there might be something to live for after all. When, several weeks later, he commits suicide himself, how will she make sense of her brutal, heartbreaking world?

description:
The Lili Albums are a series of comics that started in 1909 detailing the adventures of a young French girl sometimes known as the mischievous Lili, like Belgium’s Tintin these adventures have been reprinted again again.

However with Lili instead of reprinting the stories as they first appeared one hundred years ago the stories are reinterpreted by new writers and artists so that Lili becomes a girl of the 40’s 50’s 60’s or 90’s. 

Also while the original stories are moved into a new era, the new creators add new adventures so that in time Lili not only lived for a time on a farm, traveled to India and ran with bandits in Spain as she did in her early escapades, but would end up discovering living dinosaurs, travel in space and become increasingly more and more sexy. 

The last interpretation of Lili, her family, friends and her pet parrot took place in 1998.
name: Lili
